[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Appendix[bold]&#xa0;[bold]Improving treatments and developing new ones[bold]19. Survival
[normal] rates from cancer have doubled over the last 40 years. The science support
[normal]ed
[normal] and fund
[normal]ed by Cancer Research UK
[normal] is at the hea
[normal]rt of these improvements. In 2012/13, 
[normal]the Charity
[normal] 
[normal]spent £351 million on research in institutes, hospitals and universities across the UK. 
[normal]It is
[normal] the only charity that funds research into all types of cancer, across the development pathway from basic biology to large clinical trials. 
[normal]The Charity has
[normal] helped develop life-saving and life-extending cancer treatments, including tamoxifen
[normal] and Herceptin
[normal] f
[normal]or breast cancer and abiraterone for prostate cancer.
[normal]20.
[normal] 
[normal]A substantial proportion of Cancer Research UK's scientific funding is provided to 
[normal]its
[normal] 
[normal]five core research institutes in Glasgow, Cambridge, Oxford, Manchester and London. Cancer Research UK is one o
[normal]f the founding partners of the Francis Crick Institute - a world-class centre for interdisciplinary medical sciences, research and innovation, scheduled to open in 2015.  
[normal]21.
[normal] The Charity
[normal] 
[normal]also fund
[normal]s
[normal] work through fifteen Cancer Research UK Centres.  These C
[normal]entres provide a national framework to deliver world-leading research, improved patient care and greater local engagement. They drive local partnerships and high-calibre collaborations between universities, NHS Trusts
[normal], industry
[normal] and other cancer charities u
[normal]nder a united strategy to accelerate the translation of research into the clinic for patient benefit. 
[normal]22.
[normal] 
[normal]Providing an environment in which world-class research can thrive is crucial to 
[normal]a
[normal]chieving 
[normal]the Charity’s
[normal] 
[normal]research goals. 
[normal]I
[normal]nvestment in infrastructure 
[normal]such as 
[normal]in the
[normal] 
[normal]Centres helps to shape the research environment in the UK so that researchers can make the most of funding from 
[normal]Cancer Research UK
[normal] 
[normal]and others
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]It also enables 
[normal]the Charity 
[normal]to 
[normal]nurture the research leaders of the future. 
[normal]The Charity
[normal] 
[normal]support
[normal]s
[normal] research through 
[normal]its
[normal] 
[normal]involvement in partnerships and networks, both nationally and internationally, as well as funding the work of individual researchers across the UK.
